\f1 \cf0 <$Scr_Cs::0>
\f2\b Semantic reconciliation\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::0>
\f0 \
A prerequisite to this task is that DSP\'92s ASM refers to a SoA that can be addressed by DSC\'92s ASM when processing the received data. Since collaboration only requires to exchange the data and their semantic meaning, only two things must be assured: First, for each and every entity that is produced by the DSP in the scope of the collaboration, the DSC must be able to address the same DoA with relatable semantic meaning; Second, for each value that is produced by the DSP throughout the data exchange, the DSC must be able to refer to the same SoA with relatable quality. With quality, we refer to the principled elements that determine how the value is being generated by the DSP and how it is expected to be used by the DSC. This relates to (i) the value scale and interval addressed, the resolution and accuracy with which the value refers to the actual quantity value, the unit of measure with which the value is expressed and more [@Probst:2008hs], and to (ii) facts about the measurement or observation itself, e.g., method, measurement error, drift, sensitivity, update frequency and more [@Anonymous:2008tY]. Of course, the scope of the quality is determined by the DSC, whereas the DSP must produce the required quality attributes. \
\
Despite the capabilities of semantic reconciliation engines, e.g., [REFS], the data\'92s semantic meaning and value quality are the only but essential aspects of sIOP that require the human capability to take a glance on reality and reflect on the faithfulness with which the domain models of both agents relate to each other. The result of the human intervention is a specification on how the two domain models relate to each other \'97 a semantic alignment \'97 regarding their semantic meaning and value quality. By virtue of the coherence that is in place with the DSC software agent, and assuming a faithful alignment, the reciprocity between the DSP\'92s semantic meaning with the DSC\'92s pragmatic meaning can be guaranteed to be re-established.\
\
This role is not much different from what is required when aligning the agent\'92s data schema to the semantic standard when assuming semantic homogeneity. However, we stress that this role is the one and only need for human involvement in sIOP. \
\
Unfortunately, we cannot always assume full equivalence between the semantic meanings of the DSP and the DSC. Indeed, many variations in semantic meaning can exist. However, there is no reason to assume the existence of semantic variations for which no alignments can be specified. In fact, issues with reconciliation are an important indication that both DMs refer to distinct realities. \
\
We reflect the above with \\cref\{dp:alignment\}.\
\
