\f1 \cf0 <$Scr_Cs::0>
\f2\b Representing alignments
\f1\b0 <!$Scr_Cs::0>
\f0 \
\
A 
\f1 <$Scr_Cs::1>
\f3\i correspondence
\f1\i0 <!$Scr_Cs::1>
\f0  specifies as accurately as possible the semantic relation that exists between a pair of concepts, in order to align between the semantic meanings of interoperating agents. By exhaustively addressing all semantic relations that exist between pair of concepts of both agents, the set of correspondences collectively specify the 
\f1 <$Scr_Cs::1>
\f3\i semantic alignment
\f1\i0 <!$Scr_Cs::1>
\f0  that holds between the semantic meanings that are intended by the data that are exchanged between the two agents. The purpose of the alignment is to specify how the truth-value of expressions that are formulated in terms of the DSP, can be established by using formulations in terms of the DSC. To that end, we differentiate between the two categories of semantic differences identified above:\
\
1. 
\f1 <$Scr_Cs::1>
\f3\i Ontological differences
\f1\i0 <!$Scr_Cs::1>
\f0 : Assuming semantic compatibility, \\cref\{def:semantic-compatibility\}, variations in semantic meaning do not root in philosophical principles, but from variations in carving out reality that fit the agent\'92s purpose: perspective, context and background knowledge. These variations can be specified as formal correspondences between (constructions of) concepts from both ontologies, e.g., naming conventions, structural variations, differences in aggregation or Class-vs-Property differences, to name a few; \
1. 
\f1 <$Scr_Cs::1>
\f3\i Value quality differences
\f1\i0 <!$Scr_Cs::1>
\f0 : variations in \
  1. applied 
\f1 <$Scr_Cs::1>
\f3\i conventions
\f1\i0 <!$Scr_Cs::1>
\f0  on representing a value in its value space, for values with or without magnitudes alike, e.g., differences in value scales, units of measure or nominal properties [@Probst:2008hs]. For these variations, conversion algorithms exist that can translate values from one representation into another without inducing invalid semantics;\
  1. inherent characteristics of a value that result from the method of measurement or observation, and the measurement system applied. These are 
\f1 <$Scr_Cs::1>
\f3\i technology-induced
\f1\i0 <!$Scr_Cs::1>
\f0  qualities, and only a one-directional translation from higher to lower quality is possible, implying a technological upgrade for the DSP when the DSC demands higher quality.\
\
The language used to specify correspondences must be expressive enough to represent ontological reconciliations and convention-induced value transformations; technology-induced variations can only be identified, not resolved by any correspondence. In [@Euzenat2007;@Scharffe2011], the authors report on an investigation towards the requirements for a language to align ontologies, independent on the ontological content, resulting in EDOAL [@Scharffe2011]. This language clearly shows the distinct formalisations required between representations about ontological correspondences and those about convention-induced value transformations. This vital distinction is absent in, e.g., [@Dimou2014], that, admittedly is not designed with the purpose of specifying ontology alignments but for conversion between a wide variety of data formats and the RDF language, which is a clear example of syntax-only conversion.\
\
In conclusion, by application of 
\f1 <$Scr_Cs::1>
\f3\i conceptual connectors
\f1\i0 <!$Scr_Cs::1>
\f0  the architecture gains the capability to address a specific compound of individuals in either the source or target ontology that relate to the semantic difference at hand, reconciling the above ontological differences. Similarly, with the application of 
\f1 <$Scr_Cs::1>
\f3\i value transformation connectors
\f1\i0 <!$Scr_Cs::1>
\f0 , the architecture gains the capability to overcome the above convention-induced value differences.\
\
